  "slug": "chocolate-truffles-ganache",
  "title": "Chocolate ganache truffles",
  "subtitle": "Dark chocolate truffles rolled in cocoa",
  "excerpt": "The simplest chocolate truffles: warm cream poured over dark chocolate to form a smooth ganache, chilled until firm, rolled into balls, and tossed in cocoa powder. Twenty-four truffles from one batch.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The ganache (warm cream poured over chopped chocolate, stirred to a smooth emulsion) is documented in Auguste Escoffier, Le Guide Culinaire (1903) and earlier French sources. The truffle-rolled-in-cocoa form was popularised in late nineteenth-century Parisian chocolatiers; pre-1928 French confectionery manuals document the technique.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chocolate truffles are ganache (warm cream poured over chocolate, stirred to a smooth glossy emulsion), chilled until firm, rolled into balls and tossed in cocoa powder. The recipe takes ten minutes of work plus three hours in the fridge; the chilling does most of the labour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use a good dark chocolate at 65 to 70% cocoa. The truffles inherit the chocolate's flavour directly; cheap chocolate gives cheap truffles.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
